<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VALLEY FOCUS: VAN NUYS; MAN, 73, ACCUSED OF SEXUAL ABUSE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By THOM MROZEK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A 73-year-old North Hollywood man was charged Thursday with sexually 
assaulting three female family members, two of whom allege they were attacked 
nearly 18 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
 In a felony arrest warrant filed in Van Nuys Municipal Court, Paul Edward 
Barber was charged with 10 felony counts, including charges of continuous 
sexual abuse of the three alleged victims. 
</P>
<P>
 The charges carry a potential prison sentence of 60 years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
 Details on the case were sketchy Thursday afternoon, primarily because Barber 
had not yet been taken into custody. 
</P>
<P>
 Ventura police began investigating the case last year when a girl, now 9 years 
old, came forward and said Barber molested her from June, 1992, until 
September, 1993. 
</P>
<P>
 As the investigation continued, authorities turned up two other relatives, who 
are now 23 and 25, who said they were attacked in the summer of 1976. 
</P>
<P>
 These older allegations were not the result of recovered memories. 
</P>
<P>
 Prosecutors allege the attacks took place while the girls were visiting Barber 
in his home in the 10000 block of Keswick Street. 
</P>
<P>
 Currently, the statute of limitations on sexual assault charges prevents 
prosecutors from filing charges more than six years after the incident. 
</P>
<P>
 But an exception that became law only this year allows a criminal complaint to 
be filed, no matter how long ago the alleged offense occurred, when an adult 
alleges they were molested while a juvenile. This exception to the statute of 
limitations requires that there be "substantial sexual conduct" as well as 
corroborating evidence. 
</P>
<P>
 Prosecutors declined to comment on what corroborates the allegations made in 
relation to the alleged attacks in 1976. THOM MROZEK 
</P>
</TEXT>
