<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHERN SECTION TOUGHENS POLICY FOR FIGHTING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARTIN HENDERSON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In an attempt to crack down on the increased violence that has plagued high 
school athletic events in the last year, the Southern Section council voted 
Thursday to suspend players and coaches for fighting. 
</P>
<P>
 Beginning next fall, any player ejected for fighting or leaving the bench or 
team area during a fight will be suspended for a game.The same penalty applies 
to any coach who has similarly been ejected by an official. 
</P>
<P>
 In other action, the council: 
</P>
<P>
 -- Elected Tom Triggs, the principal at Buena Park, president-elect. He will 
become the Southern Section president in two years, at the end of Ken Gunn's 
term. Gunn, principal at Walnut High, takes over for Gary Smidderks, 
superintendent-principal at L.A. Baptist, who officiated his final meeting 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Passed a $1.245-million budget proposal for 1994-95. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Voted to support at the State level an ad hoc committee's recommendation 
that "any student transferring under the provisions of the open enrollment 
provision . . . would have immediate residential eligibility." MARTIN HENDERSON 
</P>
</TEXT>
