<HEADLINE>
<P>
FIRSTS DOMINATE NFL SCHEDULE; PRO FOOTBALL: FOX OPENS WITH COWBOYS; MONTANA 
WILL PLAY 49ERS AND FATHER-SON DUEL SET. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The 1994 NFL schedule is filled with firsts, from Fox Network's opening 
telecast featuring Super Bowl champion Dallas vs. Pittsburgh to the first 
matchup of father and son coaches -- Miami's Don Shula vs.Cincinnati's David 
Shula. 
</P>
<P>
 The Cowboys, under new Coach Barry Switzer, begin their bid for an 
unprecedented third consecutive Super Bowl title on Sunday, Sept. 4, when they 
visit Pittsburgh. It will be the first regular-season NFL game televised by 
Fox, which outbid CBS for rights to NFC games. 
</P>
<P>
 "We are very pleased with our inaugural 'NFL on Fox' schedule," Fox Sports 
President David Hill said Thursday after the league released its 1994 
regular-season schedule. "We've got the Super Bowl champion Cowboys 11 times 
and some great matchups, including (Joe) Montana's first ever game against his 
old mates in San Francisco (Sept. 11) and a rematch of the NFC championship 
game." 
</P>
<P>
 The first Sunday night game on TNT will match San Diego at Denver. ABC's 
Monday night series kicks off its 25th year with the Raiders at the 49ers. 
</P>
<P>
 Fifty-eight games are scheduled for national television. Fox or NBC will 
televise a Sunday doubleheader game to most of the nation each week, and ABC 
will show 17 Monday night games. 
</P>
<P>
 ABC also will televise the Super Bowl and the Pro Bowl. 
</P>
</TEXT>
