<HEADLINE>
<P>
SLIP OF TONGUE DOESN'T HELP EASE BOSNIA CRISIS; BALKANS: VIDEOTAPE SHOWS U.N. 
COMMANDER SAYING MUSLIM TROOPS 'BASICALLY TURNED AND RAN. . . .' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CAROL J. WILLIAMS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The stalled search for peace in Bosnia suffered more setbacks Thursday after 
the U.N. commander here insulted Muslim-led government forces and the prime 
minister said he would resume truce talks only when U.N. forces ensure security 
in battered Gorazde. 
</P>
<P>
 There were also troubling reports of Serbian heavy weapons headed for another 
vulnerable stretch of government-held territory and of tanks and artillery 
pieces being repositioned in the hills around Sarajevo. 
</P>
<P>
 Foreign mediators embarked on another diplomatic initiative to end the Bosnian 
war by meeting with leaders of the warring factions. But the distrustful 
atmosphere that has pervaded this war-weary capital since the recent Gorazde 
offensive seemed unlikely to be dispelled by repackaged proposals and hopeful 
chatter. 
</P>
<P>
 The deadly Bosnian Serb assault on Gorazde, a U.N.-protected "safe haven," has 
angered Bosnian government officials who believe that more could have been done 
by the peacekeeping force to deter the killing and destruction. 
</P>
<P>
 The U.N. commander for Bosnia, British Lt. Gen. Michael Rose, has also made 
clear that he is disgruntled with the government's failure to defend the mostly 
Muslim enclave, even though a U.N. arms embargo has prevented the government 
from acquiring the means of fighting off the heavily armed Bosnian Serbs. 
</P>
<P>
 Rose sparked an embarrassing controversy with remarks made in a brief visit to 
Gorazde on Wednesday when he was videotaped telling British soldiers that 
government troops expected the United Nations "to fight their wars for them." 
</P>
<P>
 "They basically turned and ran and left us to pick up the bits. They weren't 
that interested," Rose said of government forces whose defenses around Gorazde 
collapsed three weeks into the Serbian offensive. He also asserted that the 
numbers of dead and wounded from the monthlong Serbian assault had been 
exaggerated and that the physical damage to the "haven" was not as considerable 
as he had been led to expect. 
</P>
<P>
 Rose said the director of the Gorazde hospital, which was destroyed by Serbian 
shelling, believed that the figures of 700 killed and 2,000 wounded "were 
indeed an exaggeration." 
</P>
<P>
 His remarks prompted angry responses from Bosnian officials, who pointed out 
that the U.N. ban on delivery of weapons to any former Yugoslav republic has 
tied the hands of the fledgling government forces in battles with the Bosnian 
Serbs who inherited the vast arsenal of the Yugoslav People's Army. 
</P>
<P>
 Rose met with Bosnian Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic to smooth over the 
controversy, which U.N. spokesman Cmdr. Eric Chaperon asserted was taken out of 
context. 
</P>
<P>
 "That tape should not have been released," Chaperon said, describing Rose's 
remarks as having been made in a private discussion "from soldier to soldier" 
on various theories for the government's failure to hold a key ridge around 
Gorazde. 
</P>
<P>
 But Rose has often accused government forces of trying to take advantage of 
military opportunities opened by the U.N. presence, and the clear imbalance of 
armaments created by the U.N. embargo made his remarks appear insensitive, at 
best. 
</P>
<P>
 Silajdzic used the meeting with Rose to push for more vigorous enforcement of 
U.N. and NATO orders for withdrawal of Serbian troops and heavy weapons around 
Gorazde. Chaperon conceded that some Bosnian Serb gunmen, wearing blue police 
jumpsuits instead of army camouflage, remained inside the 1.9-mile safety zone 
declared around central Gorazde. 
</P>
<P>
 U.N. monitors have contended that Serbian forces are in "effective 
compliance." 
</P>
<P>
 U.N. officials have also hesitated to confirm that all artillery has been 
removed from a 12-mile weapons exclusion-zone around the city, saying bad 
weather and rough terrain prevent thorough verification. 
</P>
<P>
 Silajdzic said local authorities had spotted 11 artillery pieces around 
Gorazde and complained that Serbian soldiers were being allowed to hold their 
positions simply by posing as police. 
</P>
<P>
 "As soon as the ultimatum is complied with fully, we are ready to talk," he 
said after seeing Rose. 
</P>
<P>
 U.N. sources also report increasing instances of forbidden heavy weapons 
showing up within a similar exclusion zone proclaimed around Sarajevo in 
February. One senior official said the mission knows of at least five tanks, 
six antiaircraft guns and two or three howitzers over 120 millimeters in size. 
</P>
<P>
 Western-mediated peace talks have essentially been on hold since an attack on 
a Sarajevo market killed 68 people on Feb. 5, prompting the NATO threat of air 
strikes against the Bosnian Serbs unless they moved or surrendered their heavy 
weapons attacking the capital. 
</P>
<P>
 U.S. special envoy Charles Redman returned to Sarajevo to try to restart the 
peace process, and other international mediators from a recently formed 
"contact group" were due to visit rebel Serbian leaders to gauge their 
willingness to negotiate a settlement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
