<HEADLINE>
<P>
U.N. BID FOR CYPRUS SOLUTION COLLAPSES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Months of U.N.-led diplomacy aimed at persuading Greek and Turkish Cypriots to 
agree on confidence-building measures collapsed Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 After separate meetings in Nicosia with Greek Cypriot President Glafkos 
Clerides and his Turkish Cypriot counterpart, Rauf Denktash, U.N. envoy Joe 
Clark said that he had failed to bridge their differences and saw no point in 
further talks. 
</P>
<P>
 Clark, a former Canadian foreign minister, said his next move would be to 
report the outcome of his mission to U.N. Secretary General Boutros 
Boutros-Ghali. 
</P>
</TEXT>
