<HEADLINE>
<P>
LION'S SHARE OF L.A. EMMY NODS TO KCAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 KCAL-TV Channel 9 dominated nominations for the 46th annual Los Angeles Area 
Emmy Awards, accounting for 25% of the 225 finalists announced Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 KCAL's 56 nominations included best daytime newscast, best news reporting, 
best spot news and best news commentary. 
</P>
<P>
 Winners of the awards, covering programming broadcast in 1993, will be 
announced by the Academy of Television Arts & Sciences in ceremonies June 4 at 
the Pasadena Civic Auditorium. 
</P>
<P>
 Trailing KCAL on the Emmy nomination tote board were KABC-TV Channel 7 with 
33, KTTV-TV Channel 11 with 29, KCBS-TV Channel 2 with 26, KCOP-TV Channel 13 
and KTLA-TV Channel 5 with 17 each, and KCET-TV Channel 28 with 15. 
</P>
<P>
 The remainder of the nominations were spread among KNBC-TV Channel 4 with 
nine, KMEX-TV Channel 34 with six, KVEA-TV Channel 52 with four, KLCS-TV 
Channel 58 and CITY TV with three each, KOCE-TV Channel 50 and KPAS 55 with two 
apiece, and KDOC-TV Channel 56, Channel 35 and Lakewood Cable with one each. 
</P>
<P>
 Reporters Harvey Levin of KCBS and Chris Blatchford of KTTV garnered four 
nominations each, for news reporting, investigative reporting, serious 
news-feature reporting and serious minidoc. 
</P>
<P>
 The TV academy said nominations for the category of best 60-minute newscast 
will be announced in several weeks, blaming scheduling requirements for the 
delay. 
</P>
<P>
 A partial list of nominees: 
</P>
