<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: SOUTH BAY; REMOVAL OF 
DDT-TAINTED SOIL IN BACK YARDS BEGINS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 After weeks of delays, workers began removing DDT-contaminated soil on 
Thursday from two back yards near Torrance in a project ordered by the U.S. 
Environmental Protection Agency. 
</P>
<P>
 About 90 residents living close to the site have been moved to hotels at 
federal expense until the $350,000 project is completed in two weeks.That makes 
it one of the largest temporary relocations conducted by the EPA's four-state 
western regional office, a spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
 The agency announced the cleanup in March after its testing found unusually 
high levels of DDT in soil behind two homes on West 204th Street between 
Normandie and New Hampshire avenues. Federal experts remain mystified about the 
source of the DDT, which was detected at levels as much as 45 times above what 
is considered safe. 
</P>
<P>
 The project was to have begun more than three weeks ago, but residents 
protested cleanup plans and persuaded the EPA to expand the number of families 
to be relocated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
